definition.text: Cereals sown in pure crops, harvested dry for grain, and that are not recorded elsewhere under the previous items.

description.text: All areas of dried pulses and protein crops harvested dry for grain, regardless of use, shall be recorded here (including crops used for renewable energy production).

label.text: 2_01_02_Dried pulses and protein crops for the production of grain (including seed and mixtures of cereals and pulses)

definition.text: Crops sown and harvested mainly for their protein content.

label.text: 2_01_02_01_Dried pulses and protein crops of which peas, field beans and sweet lupins

definition.text: Pisum sativum L., Vicia faba L., Lupinus spp., sown in pure crops, harvested dry for grain.
Solanum tuberosum L.
Beta vulgaris L. intended for the sugar industry and alcohol production (including energy production).

Fodder beet (Beta vulgaris L.) and plants of the Brassicae family harvested mainly for animal feed, regardless whether it is the root or the stem, and other plants cultivated mainly for their roots for fodder, not mentioned elsewhere.

description.text: All harvested areas of industrial crops, regardless of use, shall be recorded here (including crops used for renewable energy production).

definition.text: Crops that are normally not sold directly for consumption because they need to be industrially processed prior to final use.
Nicotiana tabacum L.
Humulus lupulus L.
Gossypium spp., harvested for fibre as well as for oil-seeds.
Brassica napus L. (partim) and Brassica rapa L. var. sylvestris (Lam.) Briggs, grown for the production of oil, harvested as dry grains.
Helianthus annuus L., harvested as dry grains.
Glycine max L. Merril, harvested as dry grains.
Linum usitatissimum L., varieties grown mainly for producing oil, harvested as dry grains.
Other crops grown mainly for their oil content, harvested as dry grains, which are not mentioned elsewhere.
Linum usitatissimum L., varieties grown mainly for producing fibre.
Cannabis sativa L.
Other plants grown mainly for their fibre content, not mentioned elsewhere.

description.text: Culinary plants are distinguished from vegetables in that they are used in small amounts and provide flavour rather than substance to food.

definition.text: Plants or parts of plants for pharmaceutical purposes, perfume manufacture or human consumption.

description.text: Areas of crops used exclusively for renewable energy production are included.

definition.text: Other industrial crops that have not been mentioned elsewhere.

label.text: 2_01_07_Fresh vegetables, melons and strawberries of which:

definition.text: Fresh vegetables, melons and strawberries

label.text: 2_01_07_01_Outdoor or under low (not accessible) protective cover

definition.text: Fresh vegetables, melons and strawberries, outdoor or under low (non-accessible) cover.
Fresh vegetables, melons and strawberries grown on arable land in rotation with other agricultural crops.
Fresh vegetables, melons and strawberries grown on arable land in rotation with other horticultural crops.
Crops, which for the whole of their period of growth or for the predominant part of it are covered by greenhouses or fixed or mobile high cover (glass or rigid or flexible plastic).
Flowers and ornamental plants (excluding nurseries)

label.text: 2_01_08_01_Outdoor or under low (not accessible) protective cover

definition.text: Flowers and ornamental plants (excluding nurseries), outdoor or under low (not accessible) protective cover.

Flowers and ornamental plants (excluding nurseries), which for the whole of their period of growth or for the predominant part of it are covered by greenhouses or fixed or mobile high cover (glass or rigid or flexible plastic).

description.text: Green crops used for renewable energy production are included. Crops not used on the holding but sold, either for direct use on other agricultural holdings or to industry, are included.

definition.text: All green arable crops intended mainly for animal feed, grown in rotation with other crops and occupying the same parcel for less than five years (annual or multiannual fodder crops).

description.text: Mixtures of predominantly grass plants and other forage crops (usually leguminous), grazed, harvested green or as dried hay are included here.

definition.text: Grass plants for grazing, hay or silage included as a part of a normal crop rotation, lasting at least one crop year and less than five years, sown with grass or grass mixtures. The areas are broken up by ploughing or other tilling or the plants are destroyed by other means such as by herbicides before they are sown again.
Other annual or multiannual (less than five years) fodder crops.

description.text: This includes green maize directly consumed by animals (without silage) and whole cobs (grain, rachis, husk) harvested for feedstuff or silage as well as for renewable energy production.

definition.text: All forms of maize (Zea mays L.) grown mainly for silage, which is not harvested for grain (whole cob, parts of or whole plant).

description.text: Mixtures of predominantly leguminous (normally > 80 %) forage crops and grass plants, harvested green or as dried hay are included here.

definition.text: Leguminous plants grown and harvested green as the whole plant mainly for forage.

label.text: 2_01_09_02_99_Other plants harvested green not mentioned elsewhere

definition.text: Other arable crops intended mainly for animal fodder, harvested green, not mentioned elsewhere.
Areas producing seeds and seedlings for sale, excluding cereals, rice, pulses, potatoes and oil seeds.
Arable crops not included elsewhere.

description.text: The essential characteristic offallow land is that it is left torecover, normally for the wholeof a crop year.Fallow land may be:1. bare land bearing no cropsat all;2. land with spontaneousnatural growth, which may beused as feed or ploughed in;3. land sown exclusively forthe production of greenmanure (green fallow).

definition.text: All arable land included in the crop rotation system, whether worked or not, but with no intention to produce a harvest for the duration of a crop year.

description.text: Only occasional surplusproducts coming from thisarea are sold off from theholding. All areas from whichproducts are consistently soldon the market belong underother items, even if part of theproduction is consumed by theholder and his household.

definition.text: Areas devoted to the cultivation of agricultural products intended for self-consumption by the holder and his household, normally separated off from the rest of the agricultural land, and recognisable as kitchen gardens.

description.text: The land can be used forgrazing or mown for silage,hay or used for renewableenergy production.

definition.text: Land used permanently (for five years or more) to grow herbaceous forage crops, through cultivation (sown) or naturally (self-seeded), and that is not included in the crop rotation on the holding.

label.text: 2_03_01_Permanent grassland Pasture and meadow, excluding rough grazings

definition.text: Permanent pasture on good or medium quality soils. These areas can normally be used for intensive grazing.

description.text: These areas can normally beused only for extensivegrazing and are not normallymown or are mown in anextensive manner; they cannotsupport a large density ofanimals.

definition.text: Low yielding permanent grassland, usually on low quality soil, for example on hilly land and at high altitudes, usually unimproved by fertiliser, cultivation, reseeding or drainage.

label.text: 2_03_03_Permanent grassland no longer used for production purposes and eligible for the payment of subsidies

definition.text: Areas of permanent grassland and meadows no longer used for production purposes which, in line with Regulation (EC) No 1782/2003 or, where applicable, the most recent legislation, are maintained in good agricultural and environmental condition and are eligible for financial support.
Crops not grown in rotation, other than permanent grassland, which occupy the soil for a long period and yield crops over several years.

Areas containing trees, bushes and perennial berry plants other than strawberries for the production of fruit. Orchards may be of the continuous type with minimum spacing between trees or of the non-continuous type with wide spacing.
Fruit tree plantations which are traditionally cropped for producing fruits.
Fruit tree plantations which are traditionally cropped in temperate climates for producing fruits.
Fruit tree plantations which are traditionally cropped in subtropical climates for producing fruits.
Berry plantations which are traditionally cropped both in temperate and subtropical climates for producing berries.
Nut tree plantations which are traditionally cropped in temperate and subtropical climates.
Plantations of Citrus spp.
Plantations of Olea europea L.
Plantations of varieties normally grown for producing table olives.
Plantations of varieties normally grown for producing olive oil.
Plantations of Vitis vinifera L_

description.text: Grape varieties normally grown for the production of wines with a protected geographical indication (PGI) which comply with the requirements (i) of Regulation (EC) No 479/2008 or, where applicable, the most recent legislation; and (ii) the corresponding national rules.

definition.text: Grape varieties normally grown for the production of wines with a protected designation of origin (PDO) which comply with the requirements (i) of Council Regulation (EC) No 479/2008(1) or, where applicable, the most recent legislation; and (ii) the corresponding national rules.
Grape varieties normally grown for the production of wines other than PDO and PGI wines.
Grape varieties normally grown for the production of fresh grapes.
Grape varieties normally grown for the production of raisins.

description.text: (a) vine and root-stocknurseries;(b) fruit tree and berriesnurseries;(c) ornamental nurseries;(d) commercial nurseries offorest trees (excluding thosefor the holdings ownrequirements grown withinwoodland);(e) trees and bushes forplanting in gardens, parks, atthe roadside and onembankments (e.g. hedgerowplants, rose trees and otherornamental bushes,ornamental conifers), includingin all cases their stocks andyoung seedlings.

definition.text: Areas of young ligneous (woody) plants grown in the open air for subsequent transplantation:
Open-air permanent crops other than those under the previous heading and in particular those used for plaiting or weaving, harvested generally every year.

label.text: 2_04_06_01_Other permanent crops of which Christmas trees(1)

definition.text: Trees planted for commercial purposes as Christmas trees on the utilised agricultural area.
Permanent crops under glass

label.text: 2_06_Mushrooms,  energy crops and genetically modified crops

definition.text: Mushrooms,  energy crops and genetically modified crops
Cultivated mushrooms grown in buildings which have been specially erected or adapted for growing mushrooms, as well as in underground premises, caves and cellars.

label.text: 2_06_03_Energy crops (for the production of biofuels or other renewable energy)

definition.text: The production area of energy crops benefiting from the following support schemes under Regulation (EC) No 1782/2003:

label.text: 2_06_03_01_Energy crops of which on set-aside area

definition.text: The production area of energy crops benefiting of the payment linked to set-aside entitlement when production takes place on set-aside area (Council Regulation (EC) No 1782/2003, Article 55 or 56)
Genetically modified crops (GMC) mean any organism as defined in Article 2 of Council Directive 2001/18/EC(1) OJ L 106, 17.4.2001, p. 1. (1) or, where applicable, the most recent legislation.

label.text: Extensible with values at any level

definition.text: The economic activity executed on the plot, as coded accoring to EU regulation (EC) 1200/2009, annex II, chapter 2. (codes 2.01 - 2.04.07 and 2.06.03 -2.06.04).
